body:
All I did was add a particle emitter to the scene, dial in a few
parameters in the GUI, and for scripting my Update function is just:

	var scale : float = audio_data[channel] * 20;
	Target.minSize = scale;
	Target.maxSize = scale;

Where Target is the particle emitter object, and audio_data and
channel are defined globally as in the other scripts.      I think it
won't take too much tweaking to get a really dope looking waveform
shooting out of velotron's arms.

@velotron, thanks to you my battle station infrastructure is now fully operational. Ableton Live is now in control of my Unity scene via OSC. 

Today I took the knowledge you dropped last night to transform boring_old_cube into an omnidimensional vortex of self-assembling neoplasm. Midi events and waveform envelopes trigger visceral responses in a seizure inducing assault of pure information. Inevitably Xion will arise from this technological primordial substrate.  

Thanks goes out to Mab for her skills with canines, without which this singularity would not have occurred.

I just got the Arise scene up and running on my MacBook Pro complete
with the Gyroscopter powered by a new 10 port USB hub.  I hope this
hub lasts a little bit longer than the last two hubs I burned out.  I
am a stone cold USB hub killer.

Everything works, but I ran into the same Joystick Jacking problem I
got on Windows.  The problem is that the three Saitek ST290 Pro
joysticks and the Logitech racing wheel all get initialized in the
wrong order.  I tried every combination possible, rebooting between
each attempt.  Nothing worked.  The only fix is to unplug all of them
and then replug them back in the correct order each time I reboot.
Serious pain in the ass.

I have attempted to put this glitch to deliberate use because it's
important to remember that you get better results if you don't think
about it too much.  Joystick Jacking is a cheap way to achieve
unexpected results on Xion 3e9a.  But mostly, it's just annoying.

The other thing that sucks is my throttles are swapped with my Z axes.
 But that I can handle in my own code without much trouble.  I'll just
reassign them at runtime based on what operating system is detected.
Here's a bit of code that proves the concept:

//SystemDebug.js
function Start () {
	var os = SystemInfo.operatingSystem[0:3];
	switch(os) {
		case "Win":
			Debug.Log("Some people find the thought disturbing.");
			break;
		case "Mac":
			Debug.Log("I find the reality thrilling.");
			break;
	}
}


//from the console:
I find the reality thrilling.
